{
  "answer": "Sair-e-Falak (Bang-E-Dara Part 3, chapter 18) and The Wanderer (Old English Elegies, chapter 11) orient their speakers in opposite directions — one upward into the heavens, one earthward into ruin — and the difference is entirely a function of who each speaker is.\n\n**What each speaker sees:**\n\nThe Sair-e-Falak speaker, companioned by Imagination, ascends through the 'cosmic blue' and breaks free from 'that old, weary system' of earthly cycles. He sees: stars gazing at his flight in wonder; Iram (the legendary garden-paradise); Tooba's bough with singing birds; unveiled Houris; the Saqian (celestial cupbearer) pouring drink; then, far from Paradise, a dark cold void — Hell — empty of Fire and Light, whose flames are 'borrowed' things. The angel Surosh reveals to him that souls bring their own embers from the lives they wrought.\n\nThe Wanderer's speaker is an exiled thane drifting over 'the rime-cold sea' and 'ice-bound waves.' He sees: frost and snow mingled with hail; sea-birds bathing; crumbling wine-halls; 'wind-blown walls' covered with frost; the ruins of civilization ('the old work of giants'); and the spectral absence of everything once present — 'Where has the horse gone? Where has the warrior gone? Where the treasure-giver?' His imagined clasping of his dead lord dissolves back into fallow waves and falling snow.\n\n**Why each sees the cosmos this way:**\n\nThe Sair-e-Falak speaker looks upward because his constitutive faculty is Imagination — the poem literally names it as his guide. He is Iqbal's idealized spiritually free subject, unconstrained by the 'ring of dusk and dawn' (the mundane cycle of servitude and routine). His prophetic soul grants him vertical access: he can observe paradise and hell alike, and celestial revelation (Surosh) comes to him. The vision is expansive because the seer is internally elevated; his cosmos is luminous and revelatory because he is oriented by the active, ascending self.\n\nThe Wanderer's speaker looks downward because he is defined by loss and exile. His lord (the 'gold-friend') is dead, his hall is gone, his kinsmen are scattered — 'Wyrd is wholly steadfast' and has stripped him of every social anchor. This earthward condition is literal: he traverses icy seas and frozen plains, and when he tries to look inward (imagining his lord), he wakes to cold waves. What remains is only the evidence of decay. His wisdom — the 'ubi sunt' meditation on vanished horses and warriors — comes not from ascent but from accumulated suffering. He sees a world of transience and ruin because exile and bereavement have left him no other field of view; the crumbling 'enta geweorc' (the work of giants) mirrors his internal desolation.\n\nIn short: the Sair-e-Falak speaker's heavenward gaze is determined by spiritual freedom and prophetic imagination; the Wanderer's earthbound gaze is determined by social dispossession and the irreversibility of Wyrd. One is constituted by flight; the other by grief rooted to frozen ground.",
